Week 1 (Days 1–7): Foundations, no AI yet

Goal: A Flask app running locally that can accept a photo upload and fake-return a response.

Hemanya (lead/fullstack): Set up the Flask project structure, Git repo, PostgreSQL connection, basic routes (/, /scan, /recipes)
Lohith (backend): Build the /scan endpoint that accepts an image upload and returns a hardcoded fake response ({"item": "banana", "freshness": 87}) — this unblocks frontend work immediately without waiting on AI integration
Aravindhan (frontend): Plain HTML/CSS page — upload button, image preview, a results card. No JS logic yet beyond a basic fetch() call to the fake endpoint
Sri Amrita (testing/docs): Set up the README's setup instructions for real, write a .env.example, start a simple test checklist doc (what needs testing later)

End of week checkpoint: You can upload a photo in the browser and see a fake freshness result appear. This is your safety-net MVP — if nothing else works later, this still demos.

Week 2 (Days 8–14): Real Vision AI

Goal: Replace the fake response with a real GPT-4V/Gemini call.

Lohith: Get API keys, write the actual prompt sent to the vision model, parse its response into structured JSON (item, freshness %, days left). Test with 10-15 real food photos to see how accurate/consistent it actually is
Hemanya: Help debug integration issues, start on the Spoonacular recipe-matching call (send ingredient → get ranked recipes back)
Aravindhan: Update frontend to show real loading states (this call takes a few seconds, unlike the fake one), handle error cases gracefully (blurry photo, no food detected)
Sri Amrita: Start logging accuracy — for each of the 15 test photos, note what the AI got right/wrong. This becomes your "known limitations" list for the pitch, and helps you write a better prompt

Risk to watch: Freshness estimation accuracy will likely be inconsistent. Don't panic — this is normal and expected. Document it, don't hide it.

End of week checkpoint: Real photo → real AI freshness score → real recipe suggestions, working end to end.

Week 3 (Days 15–21): Community Recipe Exchange

Goal: Add the recipe-sharing feature back in, the way you and your teammate designed it.

Hemanya: Design the database schema — recipes table linked to ingredient + freshness stage + optional "family recipe" tag
Lohith: Build submission endpoint (add a recipe) and retrieval endpoint (get community recipes for a given ingredient/stage)
Aravindhan: Build the simple submission form (ingredient dropdown, not free text — this is what keeps it from feeling like Quora) and display community recipes alongside Spoonacular results
Sri Amrita: Start writing/collecting the 15-20 seed recipes now — you need real content before demo day so this section isn't empty. Reach out to family for actual recipes if you want the "grandma's wisdom" angle to feel genuine

End of week checkpoint: Scanning a banana shows both a Spoonacular recipe and a community-submitted recipe, tagged appropriately.

Week 4 (Days 22–28): Impact dashboard + polish

Goal: Add the CO₂/impact tracking, and make the whole thing look finished.

Hemanya: Build simple scan-history logging per user (or per session if you're skipping full auth) — track kg saved and CO₂ estimate over time
Lohith: Add basic session handling with Flask-Login if you're doing accounts; otherwise keep it session-based for simplicity
Aravindhan: Visual polish pass — consistent colors/spacing matching your pitch deck's purple theme, mobile-responsive check
Sri Amrita: Full test pass on every flow (upload → scan → recipe → community → dashboard), write down every bug found

End of week checkpoint: A complete, good-looking app covering every feature in your pitch deck.

Week 5 (Days 29–35): Bug fixing + demo prep — no new features

This is the most commonly skipped step, and the reason demos fail. No new features after this point.

Fix every bug from Sri Amrita's test list, prioritizing anything that would break a live demo
Deploy to Render and test the deployed version, not just localhost (things often break differently once deployed)
Prepare 3-4 pre-tested demo photos that you know work well, so your live demo doesn't rely on a random fridge item behaving unpredictably
Rehearse the full demo as a team at least 3 times, timed
Days 36–37: Buffer + final polish
Final rehearsal, fix anything that broke during deployment testing
Update slides/pitch deck if anything changed since submission
Get sleep before the actual event — an exhausted team fumbles demos more than a slightly-less-polished app does
